The options then are: (1) to replace the smoke generating mosquito coils with non-smoke mosquito controlling economical methods (such as liquid vaporisers); and (2) remove the unwanted combustion particles generated by the fillers used in coils so as to make the coil a “cleaner” option to reduce exposure and respiratory health risks. The present study focused on the second option and assessed the feasibility of using unipolar ionisers in mitigating the hazardous particulates without affecting the vapour-bound insecticide compounds in the mosquito coils. As the ionisers reduce only the unnecessary filler particulates, the efficacy of mosquito coil would not be compromised due to ioniser operation. In this context, understanding the size dependency of the particulate reduction is important in order to strengthen the studies on ioniser induced particle reduction. The objectives of this work are:


Understanding the mosquito coil aerosol emissions in terms of size segregated aerosol concentration profiles;

Studying the depletion characteristics of mosquito coil generated aerosols in presence of ioniser;

Estimating size-dependent concentration reduction factors for ioniser-aided removal;

Assessing inhalation risk reduction by adopting ioniser-based mitigation technique.
